segments.text: I just... Buck, did you find the agency too confining to work for?
It sort of bothers me that you kind of come and go with such regularity in the agency.
Was that what was wrong?
Yeah, it was just, no, it's the same thing, a sense of freedom.
I didn't want to, I felt like I was incumbent with the agency, but now and then I just get worried of it.
I mean, the type of work I was doing, assignments.
What I was trying to get away with myself, just no more assignments.
Which I did not.
Only as an assignment I took on with this A&M one, but I haven't, I don't take any more.
But just did what other prevailed of it, John Lentz and Bucky, other Aggie alumni, there was an artist and it's up to you to do it, and it kept on.
I said, okay, I'll do it.
But I didn't want it.
Because I was afraid of it.
I was more or less, didn't have free reign, but they let me go.
But I had some things I wanted to put in there.
I still have some of my best subjects that I haven't,
Because I feel small ones.
Oh my God, the beautiful things I've done.
It's like when I'm taking a roadie at the hospital.
All I knew was acting polo and all that type of thing.
But I still have them filming.
The bonfire, I stayed with that for a week, just watching that.
But I've got all those sketches of that, but I never have.
I've lost the focus.
I haven't done the library.
Some of the library I want to work on.
But I couldn't do them all.
It was eight.
They finally started with 40, went to six, and then to eight, because it'll take 15 or 20 to really cope with this thing.
But I'd rather do it now and do some more, but on my own volition.
I'm doing this for boxing.
Well, I have to do that.
I'm doing it for boxing.
If somebody is behind me or stipulating anything, I fold up.
I'm conscious somebody's going to say, hey, I believe you better do it.
But I won't do it.
I'm protecting myself.
Mm-hmm.
And you think that's because of the agency work?
You think the pressure working with the agency all that time?
Oh, yeah.
It was something.
It had a lot to do with it.
But yeah, I've had free reign to do it.
I don't want to actually do this type of thing.
But I've got some other things.
But I'll do them on my own.
Mostly action things.
How did your marriage survive under the pressure of the agency?
You seemed to have been gone all the time.
Oh, no.
Two months.
I was out on road trips for quite a bit, maybe a week or so at a time, but at the time I was gone for three weeks at most, I believe.
Then I took on some other work, back to Interwoven, up in the Matthews Ranch.
And then Book, and then with Carl Hurt, I was a pastor a week.
That was a beautiful assignment, but I loved it.
But, oh no, I just, I don't want any more.
But I don't know.
Which way to go?
Sometimes I just don't know.
I'm still restless, isn't it?
When did you go?
You go to Italy when?
You do a series of things, an Italian series?
Oh, I did a tremendous lot of Italian.
I stayed in Italy about two months, but I, God, I turned out a hundred or so in one of those.
Every day.
I was so enthralled with the same
that I just, and then I'm really, and essentially in Rome, there's Florence, and I went to Venice, I just, I'll case the boot.
And I get, oh God, the material.
And Ford, all Britain here, has this place out here, I don't know what the region was, has the biggest collection of Italian things.
How did you decide upon Italy?
My brother was, he was in Italy for 12 years, a sculptor, he was the head of the Department of Sculpture in Rome, the Academy in Rome.
Oh, he's a
Because my brother, that's another thing, but he was, I think, a top-ranking sculptor, because he died in 1971 in America.
Oh, he's tremendous.
He started in Carl Miller's.
He was in Sweden, in the court with King Gustav, doing fine.
But he's the one that's had a career that's colorful.
But I was with him two months.
But I had plans with him, because that's what, God, when he died, I think another segment of my world just dropped away.
Because I felt he was so strong with key to key, I think, and everything I moved.
But, man, it was a joy.
But we had great plans, wasn't it, to work together, get a studio scene.
We thought about hunting, and he said, somewhere I want a place where I can do my casting.
Let's work, let's be together.
That was taken care of.
How many children were there in your family?
Five.
Five.
That's what I thought.
Poor boy and his sister.
She died.
And how many of you went into art?
Well, to be truthful with you, the only one that didn't was my sister.
Now Ted, my brother, he just started going to the porcelains, like ceramics.
There's one in the center, that white one in there.
I think it was Wayne's office.
And Pete, my brother, was his
He got him to sculpt it.
He didn't know he hadn't, he was never going to do it until Rube Lee did sculpt one of his pieces.
He was driving a truck in Cuero.
And he was doing a sculpture on the side.
And he was doing these magnificent things.
And she saw the plasma.
God, look at that.
That man got the touch.
Because she knew sculpture was a good one.
So that's when we
Got him out of Cuero in a hurry and put him to work with Bill McVeigh, now he's teaching in the museum.
And he came rolling up and he went to see Millis, the top man in the world, from Sweden, called Millis in Cranbrook.
And Carl's always waiting, took him in a paper sack, took one head of him, got on the bus, we sent him up there, are you going to call Millis?
Rupert Lee was my wife.
And Millis said, my God, my boy, I think I can use you, I've been waiting for you.
What's he sent, I don't know,
So he went, stayed with Miller's Guard, and he went through the Second World War, Pete did.
He was, he got killed then.
He was right in the middle of the Battle of the Bulge and everything, but he was, but he just got to squeak through that, right in action.
But he came back, he was a wreck too.
Oh, God, he was a wreck.
But I took him in, told, we tried to take him to Cuero, and my mother said, Buck, you just have to do something with him, because we can't, he can't, he just was, just an almost a raving maniac.
Was it from being shell-shocked?
Shell-shocked and no communication in Cuero.
He tried to bring a lot of people in, more or less in the art world.
I'm that way to service, but not like he was.
But an operator to Houston had kept him here once, and he wanted to go back there.
And he had some nice contacts, but he came there.
He went one year to A&M.
He said, this is not my cup of tea.
Hell, I'll get out of here.
I said, why didn't you see it on television?
I said, I don't want to.
I said, I loved it.
He's been around these people, Pete McGrath.
The association didn't have to be on.
But he didn't.
He said he was.
But he was a delightful person.
Now he's the one who went on to Italy and worked in sculpture.
All right.
Now what about your third brother?
Dave is not, he was a mechanical engineer.
He graduated in 25.
But he was a
wonderful craftsman, Woodward.
He got into woodwork, built his own thing.
He went to Charlotte, North Carolina with the Oak Manufacturing.
You know, and he was there, he married there, he got a home.
Then he started in woodwork.
That thing down, he'd done some beautiful furniture and things.
But the base of that tree, insect and tree in the middle, that's what Pete did.
I don't know whether he ever cast that thing.
I don't know.
God almighty.
But anyhow, he made the base.
And Dave does a lot of furniture with this on his own.
But he hasn't got a feeling for art at all.
But there was another manifestation of what you call it.
There still is Christ.
Only one that didn't.
They say Ted's a ceramic, but there's these ceramic buddies.
So the talent was there, but the main thing is to go to prove that you can have all the talent in the world that can remain latent.
Sometimes an artist, unless you have tremendous desire to go ahead with it, you'll die on the vine.
You had to have a lift, and we took Pete off that truck and sent him on to the platform.
And I never did, I just went on my own most of the time.
I got some help in here, and people say it was relative, I don't know how it was.
I get some plaudits now and then, but you had to have constructive help, I guess, wasn't anything else, just innate feeling.
And I get a lot of that here, even with Frank and Wayne.
It's associated, see, but in the octet, it shouldn't be up there.

Anyhow, and Sharon Steen, I don't know what's her name, but she's the one that sent the feeling of all this encouragement, just the right thing, but how is it that the percent is one of the most remarkable women I've ever met in my life?
But she's running for mayor, put her on now.
And God,
But they gave me this place, and until you see it, you don't see where we went.
Extremely went through to get a spot for me.
They put this old filling station up there, moved it in, west off, convey with it.
It was a mess, filthy mess.
Took it, made a pad, and stood you out of it.
That's my, that's my, that's my...
I call it my domain, but I've got, it's on 1100 acres, I'm right in the middle of it out there, and I've got 60 beautiful cattle, crossbred cattle that belong to Jeff, and Jeff's a freshman at A&M.
And then a coyote tonight, but it's an ultimate time, it's rather desolate, I'll tell you that, but I don't know.
What was your father's reaction to all you guys going into art?
Did he?
He just tolerated it.
I thought maybe after you broke the ground.
I broke the ground, yes.
And I broke it for Pete.
Pete didn't want to go there.
He may have given it a try.
And I broke the ground in a lot of ways.
I took a lot of that discipline.
I was on heavy discipline all the time, but I gave unmedicated help, too.
I mean, I really did.
Oh, my God.
I mean, the thing.
Just running away all the time.
Escape complex.
I rode freight.
I didn't appear every damn weekend.
I kept the freight and go somewhere.
Fritz Handler had his little garden class out there where we did our landscaping.
I'd be going by, there was about one place, H&TC would come through.
He said, put your hoe down, Buck, there it is.
I'd get on, I'd go down somewhere.
Did you pick out any place in particular, or just go over?
No, I didn't.
Well, that's another thing.
Because it had its compensations, because that's where I got to see my Texas, didn't have a car.
But even the Mahe oil fields, I knew about those at night.
I was here at oil fields at night.
So I took, I got on a cow catcher here in H&TC, one of them, because they stopped putting me off.
But then I saw my first oil field at night around Mahe, across the canyon.
But I, I, but it was just, it's a tremendous restlessness.
That's when, of course, I was the beachcomber down in, you know, Magnolia, not exactly, but I lived on the coast with the old oyster fishermen and tents and goat milk and everything else.
But the line just... Now, when you, when you just, when you just caught this freight and went out someplace, did you draw while you were out there?
Just, just looked?
Just looked.
Put it here.
I do a lot of that.
I photograph my mind.
I can drive through the country.
and start the camera snapping thing down, come back here and almost put it down.
I taught, I teach my class that, to just go here and just concentrate, concentrate.
Focus on your mind, if it's exciting enough.
But I do a lot of that.
I can come back and almost, I'll miss some aspects of it, but I do that quite often, because as soon as I get there, I don't have a camera with me.
I just have to make a feel about it.
Now the night, no, not the other night, excuse me, but the other day,
A few weeks ago, we went down, called Kruger, my, it was Polly's son, Al, Aggie style, but he called me and said, Buck, come on down here.
I said, boy, we've got, we've been having beautiful weather.
Maybe we'll have this weekend in the hooping cranes.
Maybe we can see them.
Close to there.
So I have seen them before, but the way out in the marsh, it's the head sticking up.
And he said, come on.
And I went down, and I have a, he only had one of his condominiums.
I mean, it's my, anytime I wanted.
So I went down there, and
We went out that Sunday morning.
All of a sudden we saw one or two of them marching just around a spit there.
And of course the command was the same spit.
And there were seven of them.
The closest you'll ever see the darn thing.
And they were cavorting around.
But usually you never see it with three together.
But I went out, of course, I made a number of sketches.
I didn't take pictures.
Some of them, you couldn't, it was too far away.
But I put it all down.
That's what I had in my field notes.
different ones.
I'll put, from that I'll go on, I'll make it some nature studies up close.
But I got the antics and everything, the way they behaved.
But I didn't, I sat in that boat, sketch, sketch, sketch, talked to all the people down there.
Then I found a beautiful array of, oh, hundreds and hundreds of white pelicans were soaring above it with buzzards.
And all of a sudden they came down and got on this spit of land.
Oh, here it is, right here.
This was quick, you know.
That's a gorgeous book.
And so you can remember things like that and just come back and do it.
Good heavens.
Did it just come through practice?
Was it because you were working in the daytime?
We were doing so many of them.
Hundreds and hundreds of times.
And all I'm feeling, God, this one is just great.
I had an unusual one I got the other day.
It's funny, but it's not essential.
But I was down in Seafloor and I found this little vent here and an oleander bush was coming out.
It was called a Maverick Oleander, but I found that down there.
I've been doing these all day, and then I saw a pencil, and I got this at Lyons.
There's no gin there, just a shack that, well, Haskell closed by, so I got on down there.
But it's just things like this, and I don't know if it's a particular, but it's just a documentary type.
But my gins,
I have a feast for them, the old gems, with the stacks.
I mean, I have a collection of about 100 of the old gems, and I don't know where to put them down.
Oh, good.
You're going to do all those for a book?
No, I'll just be sitting.
Maybe get a book out of it later on.
I mean, just on that one premise, on the gems.
But I do it because I do it.
A cotton man will buy them like nobody did.
Yeah.
I've always got a lot of papers this far.
I don't do anything for that time.
I just do it for a living.
The new jens you can have.
I've been out on the site.
I just plate them and take all the new electric jens.
They just leave me cold.
But the old jens?
Oh, yeah.
God.
Oh, they got that composition.
One down in Cuero.
I'm going to do that one.
Or in Yorktown.
I sold all those.
Do you think all your architecture training helped you get these kinds of ideas?
This is essentially architecture.
I don't like architecture as a whole.
I like restorations.
I go down to these places like Round Top and off there and through there, and I've got a whole series that I don't have anymore.
But I just put those down.
And architecture cleaning has helped, but I don't like anything slick.
People call up and say, hey, I could just restore the new house down at Round Top or Felt or Burton in the city.
It's all slicked up beautifully.
I said, I'm sorry, but I preferred when it was under
was punished.
I mean, that's where, yeah.
But I don't like to do, oh, I get calls all the time.
People are so proud.
It's wonderful that they're restoring them and keeping them intact.
Beautiful.
But it don't make, go for subject matter to me.
Sometimes, I like old brick, but, but restoration, that's another one of the facets I've gotten into the help on,
We're keeping things intact, but essentially courthouses.
I've done that, a square courthouse I've ever contacted, on Dewitt County.
And I found out about that, and I went and met with some of the women.
I said, my God, don't do that.
And I ran some more of this campaign for just keeping out a facade and refurbishing the interior, make the modern out with glass petitions and everything, actually lower the ceiling.
Oh, it fought me.
God, it gave me hell.
And finally they did accomplish it, but it cost them so much money, they were just mad furious.
And they said, oh Lord, I created a wave of indignation.
But anyhow, now they just completely have it.
And it's comfortable, and they feel important, you know, they don't have the old stinky, dark woodwork.
But no, everybody's very happy.
In Victoria, they were going to tear it down.
I wrote an editorial, and they kept calling on me.
And Dallas wanted me to keep there, of course.
But I just can't allocate all my time to that, because I'd rather continue with what I have to do.
That's my art.
But this is important, though.
It's contributing.
I think that's a great thing.
It's so essential, I think, that while you go along, instead of being so self-centered and selfish, but go ahead and contribute.
I don't care what it is, whether it's any causes, right?
A lot of things, too.
Restorations.
Do you find yourself more productive now or less productive?
I think I'm more productive.
I think about 180 degree turn almost.
Because I had a path operation, but I had a time coming up.
But I won't go into it, but the seams broke on it, and then we opened up everything, and infection, blood clots, and the one thing after that.
But I don't know if I've got it behind me now.
I feel just about as productive as I was in my life.
Maybe more so.
Do you feel like that you've
Or now that you don't have the pressure of the agency behind you, do you feel like you have more time to do it in leisure?
Or do you feel pressed now to do things?
I don't feel pressed.
I don't want to be pressed on anything.
Like this book of Frank's.
I've got time on it, but we're going to use it.
Oh, we had a big meeting yesterday.
Use the old stuff, and some of this will be used in that.
But no pressure.
But I said, Frank, let's go set a deadline.
So we'll get the things in.
a big show in fall of 70s this year, and then 78 will come out with a book, but not this year.
I don't want that.
If I get the material into this year, then they can go from then on, because I have to do the narration to some extent.
I mean, the research I've done, which I did these other two books, but of course they edited.
I've got to put it out, because I have my own vernacular in writing, and I do like, like Toby traveled with him a lot, man.
He said, God Almighty, Buckingham
Butch said the King's English put poetry right your way.
So I don't care.
He criticized him.
But that's another thing.
I've had tremendous good luck.
Well, not good luck, but advantage that I would travel with Mr. Dobie.
People don't know that.
We went out to the field all the time.
When did you travel with Dobie?
Oh, yeah, back in about 10 days ago.
Before he died.
Oh, I had to escapade with him against the doctor's orders when he was a sick man.
I took him out.
Oh.
But
But he was, it was such a delight, and the man was so delighted.
He went, I can't tell you the story, too.
Several times I took his doctor's orders, I took him out.
He'd be, but please do this for me.
I'm tired of being on the shelf.
Well, damn it, you don't have to be on the shelf.
Let's go.
And I came back with him.
We were all at night.
Oh, thank God for you.
Better if you like me.
And walked away, but I was with him lots of times.
Better check with him.
They're beautiful people.
Whew!
That's gone.
That's another wonderful affiliation I had.
But I didn't come into their lives away until, oh, what's, the mid-60s, I guess.
But it was a delight.
I could have, if Mr. Dobie had lived, Frank, of course.
We had lots of things in mind we wanted to do.
He wanted to visit with me, of course.
But, gee, it's a joy to be with those people.
You must have known them in and around Austin then.
Yeah.
Yeah, he had his ranch out there.
Of course, now he has Bassano at that time.
He got a new ranch, bought some other property.
But I went out with Bassano quite a few times.
And we wanted to go to Beaver and many places, but his family were brought away.
He had his ranch, his big ranch.
He was a wonderful fellow.
I mean, he could be very raucous and tough, but he was kind.
He was constructive.
But we hit it off nicely.
Frank Vandervoort, I got closer to him than anybody else.
I knew him through the UDC work.
But next to home, I take it from here.
I think that you'll go back to Quirrell then for a while and work around there.
Do you intend to stick with primarily native Texas scenes, Bob?
I think I will.
No more battalion scenes?
I don't know.
Why not?
Why should I?
Can't think of any particular reason why you should at all?
Because this is embedded in Portland.
It's deep in me, so much of it.
That I go other places, I might do things.
Even Italy was
But the Roman Forum, my God, I was in joy.
1950, 1960, right, just at the Forum.
And I don't know, they sold, married and sold them off and on different places in Venice.
But I come back, oh, it's a huge lift to see the beauty of those things.
And of course, you always think, isn't that what it does?
Creating your memories, my God.
How did they build the Colosseum?
Just look at the heart.
And it's an odd violin, my God.
But it doesn't come back here.
But this is, there's so much Texas has to contribute yet.
I want to put out a document or whatever it is.
I think that's my slide.
Let's just put it that way.
I think this is what you should do as so designated by the man above.
You think an artist ought to do things in his regions, things he has an emotional feel for?
No, I don't think I would.
Whatever comes off with you, I mean, it excites you, it stimulates you, inspires you.
No.
I don't believe that.
You have to, because I am more of a dedicated Texan than most artists.
On average, artists don't give a tank a damn about Texas.
They don't history.
They don't, but you have to study the history and know it.
Probe it.
Talk to people.
No, I, so much that's done, my art is just for pictorial sense.
It's called Superman.
I'd be superficial, but it's scenic entirely.
But there's much more in it.
Especially if you do housework, you have to be able to walk into a door and see how inside a window, but there's just a heck of a lot there.
It's hard to describe.
But you feel it.
Oh, thanks God, because I love the coast.
I've been having some escapades on the coast.
I've been through one of the hurricanes.
I really did barely squeak through.
If I ride it out, I learned the hard way.
But I found, God, it was magnificent.
I don't know, it's a thing like challenges, challenges, challenges.
What do you need of them?
Give you stimulus.
Do you think in a way, Buck, that you'll be preserving past Texas culture in the sense of this work?
How me?
I don't know.
It's a very wonderful culture.
I look at Elizabeth and I, because she did all this statuary, what she has been doing.
We did that, but she's a more or less of a known entity in the eyes of the modern art world.
I'm going to do welding stuff, crap.
I thought, hell with you.
Guy's going to do welding, I'll do it too.
Pete and I said, let's make my place at home.
Just the junk, you ought to weld it.
And I wouldn't want to do it, just for the hell of it.
I like some of it, but I think it'd be fun.
It would be, Pete and I want to do it together.
I said, let's go ahead.
They think it's so damn good, let's show them we're better.
Oh, it's good.
I don't know if they're going to stay South American.
It's hard to get serious.
You keep a sense of humor.
God knows.
That is so important.
You think that would be the advice you'd give to a young artist, to always keep a sense of humor?
I think to some extent.
But they're too serious.
Most of them are.
They're highly sensitive.
They react to any kind of adverse criticism.
You have to be more than an artist.
You've got to be a human being, a strong one.
That's it.
And if you want to be associated with the cedar choppers, which I do.
Of course, I'm not going to go out and oil raid with them.
It's the roughest element you can find in mankind, and you'll see what that...
They all contribute to him.
Maybe Holmes' one philosophy about it, but I don't know.
I feel sorry for the average artist.
I don't think they had the opportunity.
I feel sorry for them.
It's a shame they can't, whether they could accept things that I've been through.
I don't know.
It's hard to tell.
But that's a whole other subject.
I look at everything as a new adventure, and there's something that's different than, you know, like I said, the assignment's over with me.
Everything's on my own volition.
But did you ever think about going to Europe and doing work in the 20s?
Europe?
Yeah.
No.
Never worked, right?
Did it go over there?
I had sandwiches.
I could have been sent over there, but even the architect playing with Tompkins Swain would go there and take a look at some ironwork in Spain.
I, right now, I think I was foolish not doing it, but I was a little bit skittish about what I did.
If I'd have gone with somebody, I think maybe I should have done something, I don't know.
I don't look back at anything.
Whatever happened, happened.
It was for a purpose.
My pattern's been laying, whatever the pattern was like, the schedule, whatever.
I don't like planning anything anymore.
My deadline's too long.
